# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fbx-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics, contrary to what the name suggests, are most often displayed on two-dimensional displays.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike 3D film and similar techniques, the result is two-dimensional, without visual depth.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] More often, 3D graphics are being displayed on 3D displays, like in virtual reality systems.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3D graphics stand in contrast to 2D computer graphics which typically use completely different methods and formats for creation and rendering.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics rely on many of the same algorithms as 2D computer vector graphics in the wire-frame model and 2D computer raster graphics in the final rendered display.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] In computer graphics software, 2D applications may use 3D techniques to achieve effects such as lighting, and similarly, 3D may use some 2D rendering techniques.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] The objects in 3D computer graphics are often referred to as 3D models.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike the rendered image, a model's data is contained within a graphical data file.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] A 3D model is a mathematical representation of *any* three-dimensional object; a model is not technically a *graphic* until it is displayed.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] A model can be displayed visually as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering, or it can be used in non-graphical computer simulations and calculations.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] With 3D printing, models are rendered into an actual 3D physical representation of themselves, with some limitations as to how accurately the physical model can match the virtual model.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] William Fetter was credited with coining the term *computer graphics* in 1961 to describe his work at Boeing.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] An early example of interactive 3-D computer graphics was explored in 1963 by the Sketchpad program at Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] One of the first displays of computer animation was *Futureworld* (1976), which included an animation of a human face and a hand that had originally appeared in the 1972 experimental short *A Computer Animated Hand*, created by University of Utah students Edwin Catmull and Fred Parke.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software began appearing for home computers in the late 1970s.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] The earliest known example is *3D Art Graphics*, a set of 3-D computer graphics effects, written by Kazumasa Mitazawa and released in June 1978 for the Apple II.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Virtual Reality 3D is a version of 3D computer graphics.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Although the first VR headsets appeared in the late 1950s, VR did not become widely popular until the 2000s.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] In 2012 the Oculus was released and since then, the 3D VR headset world has expanded.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] The modeling describes the process of forming the shape of an object.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] The two most common sources of 3D models are those that an artist or engineer originates on a computer with a 3D modeling tool, or models scanned into a computer from real-world objects (polygonal modeling, patch modeling, and NURBS modeling are some popular tools used in 3D modeling).
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Models can also be produced procedurally or via physical simulation.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Basically, a 3D model is formed from points called vertices that define the shape and form polygons.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] A polygon is an area formed from at least three vertices (a triangle).
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] The overall integrity of the model and its suitability to use in animation depend on the structure of the polygons.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Before rendering into an image, objects must be laid out in a 3D scene.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] This defines spatial relationships between objects, including location and size.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Animation refers to the temporal description of an object (i.e., how it moves and deforms over time).
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Popular methods include keyframing, inverse kinematics, and motion-capture).
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] These techniques are often used in combination.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] As with animation, physical simulation also specifies motion.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Stop Motion has multiple categories within such as Claymation, Cutout, Silhouette, Lego, Puppets, and Pixelation.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Claymation is the use of models made of clay used for an animation.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples are Clay Fighter and Clay Jam.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Lego animation is one of the more common types of stop motion.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Lego stop motion is the use of the figures themselves moving around.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples of this are Lego Island and Lego Harry Potter.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Rendering converts a model into an image either by simulating light transport to get photo-realistic images, or by applying an art style as in non-photorealistic rendering.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] The two basic operations in realistic rendering are transport (how much light gets from one place to another) and scattering (how surfaces interact with light).
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] This step is usually performed using 3-D computer graphics software or a 3-D graphics API.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Altering the scene into a suitable form for rendering also involves 3D projection, which displays a three-dimensional image in two dimensions.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Materials and textures are properties that the render engine uses to render the model.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] One can give the model materials to tell the render engine how to treat light when it hits the surface.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Textures are used to give the material color using a color or albedo map, or give the surface features using a bump map or normal map.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] It can also be used to deform the model itself using a displacement map.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software produces computer-generated imagery (CGI) through 3D modeling and 3D rendering or produces 3-D models for analytical, scientific, entertainment, and industrial purposes.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] There are many varieties of files supporting 3-D graphics, for example, Blender (.blend), Wavefront (.obj), .fbx and .x DirectX files.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Each file type generally tends to have its own unique data structure.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Each file format can be accessed through its respective applications, such as DirectX files, and Quake.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Alternatively, files can be accessed through third-party standalone programs, or via manual decompilation.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling software is a class of 3-D computer graphics software used to produce 3-D models.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications or modelers.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling starts by describing 3 display models: drawing points, drawing lines and drawing triangles and other polygonal patches.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers allow users to create and alter models via their 3-D mesh.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Users can add, subtract, stretch and otherwise change the mesh to their desire.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be viewed from a variety of angles, usually simultaneously.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be rotated and the view can be zoomed in and out.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers can export their models to files, which can then be imported into other applications as long as the metadata are compatible.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Many modelers allow importers and exporters to be plugged-in, so they can read and write data in the native formats of other applications.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Most 3-D modelers contain a number of related features, such as ray tracers and other rendering alternatives and texture mapping facilities.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some also contain features that support or allow animation of models.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some may be able to generate full-motion video of a series of rendered scenes (i.e. animation).
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Computer-aided design software may employ the same fundamental 3-D modeling techniques that 3-D modeling software uses but their goal differs.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] They are used in computer-aided engineering, computer-aided manufacturing, Finite element analysis, product lifecycle management, 3D printing and computer-aided architectural design.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] After producing a video, studios then edit or composite the video using programs such as Adobe Premiere Pro or Final Cut Pro at the mid-level, or Autodesk Combustion, Digital Fusion, Shake at the high-end.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Match moving software is commonly used to match live video with computer-generated video, keeping the two in sync as the camera moves.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Use of real-time computer graphics engines to create a cinematic production is called machinima.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Not all computer graphics that appear 3D are based on a wireframe model.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics with 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Visual artists may also copy or visualize 3D effects and manually render photo-realistic effects without the use of filters.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some video games use 2.5D graphics, involving restricted projections of three-dimensional environments, such as isometric graphics or virtual cameras with fixed angles, either as a way to improve performance of the game engine or for stylistic and gameplay concerns.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] By contrast, games using 3D computer graphics without such restrictions are said to use true 3D.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Cutout is the use of flat materials such as paper.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Everything is cut out of paper including the environment, characters, and even some props.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Silhouette is similar to cutouts except they are one solid color, black.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Puppets are dolls and different puppets used in the game.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] An example of this would be Yoshi's Wooly World.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] Pixelation is when the entire game appears pixelated, this includes the characters and the environment around them.
[src:fbx-format/3d-computer-graphics] One example of this is seen in Shovel Knight.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] In 3D computer graphics, **3D modeling** is the process of developing a mathematical coordinate-based representation of a surface of an object (inanimate or living) in three dimensions via specialized software by manipulating edges, vertices, and polygons in a simulated 3D space.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Three-dimensional (3D) models represent a physical body using a collection of points in 3D space, connected by various geometric entities such as triangles, lines, curved surfaces, etc.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Being a collection of data (points and other information), 3D models can be created manually, algorithmically (procedural modeling), or by scanning.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Their surfaces may be further defined with texture mapping.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The product is called a 3D model, while someone who works with 3D models may be referred to as a 3D artist or a 3D modeler.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] A 3D model can also be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering or used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] 3D models may be created automatically or manually.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The 3D model can be physically created using 3D printing devices that form 2D layers of the model with three-dimensional material, one layer at a time.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Without a 3D model, a 3D print is not possible.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] 3D modeling software is a class of 3D computer graphics software used to produce 3D models.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] 3D models are now widely used anywhere in 3D graphics and CAD but their history predates the widespread use of 3D graphics on personal computers.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] In the past, many computer games used pre-rendered images of 3D models as sprites before computers could render them in real-time.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The designer can then see the model in various directions and views, this can help the designer see if the object is created as intended to compared to their original vision.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Seeing the design this way can help the designer or company figure out changes or improvements needed to the product.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Simple wireframes were the first versions of early 3D models, which were mainly used to view construction plans and mechanical parts.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Better graphics hardware and software allowed for the creation of solid and surface models in the 1970s and 1980s, giving designers a more realistic and clear representation of physical objects.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] By the 1990s, parametric modeling became popular, letting designers change a model by changing its basic parameters instead of redrawing it from scratch.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Thanks to virtual reality, artificial intelligence and generative design tools, 3D modeling today goes past engineering and is influencing fields like animation, gaming, product design and cinema.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Solid and shell modeling can create functionally identical objects.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Differences between them are mostly variations in the way they are created and edited and conventions of use in various fields and differences in types of approximations between the model and reality.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Shell models must be manifold (having no holes or cracks in the shell) to be meaningful as a real object.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] For example, in a shell model of a cube, all six sides must be connected with no gaps in the edges or the corners.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Polygonal meshes (and to a lesser extent, subdivision surfaces) are by far the most common representation.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Level sets are a useful representation for deforming surfaces that undergo many topological changes, such as fluids.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The process of transforming representations of objects, such as the middle point coordinate of a sphere and a point on its circumference, into a polygon representation of a sphere is called tessellation.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] This step is used in polygon-based rendering, where objects are broken down from abstract representations ("primitives") such as spheres, cones etc., to so-called *meshes*, which are nets of interconnected triangles.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Meshes of triangles (instead of e.g., squares) are popular as they have proven to be easy to rasterize (the surface described by each triangle is planar, so the projection is always convex).
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Polygon representations are not used in all rendering techniques, and in these cases the tessellation step is not included in the transition from abstract representation to rendered scene.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The modeling stage consists of shaping individual objects that are later used in the scene.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] In some cases, there is no strict distinction between these phases; in such cases, modeling is just part of the scene creation process (this is the case, for example, with Caligari trueSpace and Realsoft 3D).
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] 3D models can also be created using the technique of Photogrammetry with dedicated programs such as RealityCapture, Metashape and 3DF Zephyr.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Cleanup and further processing can be performed with applications such as MeshLab, the GigaMesh Software Framework, netfabb or MeshMixer.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Photogrammetry creates models using algorithms to interpret the shape and texture of real-world objects and environments based on photographs taken from many angles of the subject.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Complex materials such as blowing sand, clouds, and liquid sprays are modeled with particle systems, and are a mass of 3D coordinates which have either points, polygons, texture splats or sprites assigned to them.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] There are a variety of 3D modeling programs that can be used in the industries of engineering, interior design, film and others.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Each 3D modeling software has specific capabilities and can be utilized to fulfill demands for the industry.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Many programs include export options to form a g-code, applicable to additive or subtractive manufacturing machinery.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] G-code (computer numerical control) works with automated technology to form a real-world rendition of 3D models.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] This code is a specific set of instructions to carry out steps of a product's manufacturing.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The first widely available commercial application of human virtual models appeared in 1998 on the Lands' End web site.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The human virtual models were created by the company My Virtual Mode Inc. and enabled users to create a model of themselves and try on 3D clothing.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] There are several modern programs that allow for the creation of virtual human models (Poser being one example).
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The development of cloth simulation software such as Marvelous Designer, CLO3D and Optitex, has enabled artists and fashion designers to model dynamic 3D clothing on the computer.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Dynamic 3D clothing is used for virtual fashion catalogs, as well as for dressing 3D characters for video games, 3D animation movies, for digital doubles in movies, as a creation tool for digital fashion brands, as well as for making clothes for avatars in virtual worlds such as SecondLife.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Disadvantages compared to 2D photorealistic rendering may include a software learning curve and difficulty achieving certain photorealistic effects.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Some photorealistic effects may be achieved with special rendering filters included in the 3D modeling software.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] For the best of both worlds, some artists use a combination of 3D modeling followed by editing the 2D computer-rendered images from the 3D model.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] A large market for 3D models (as well as 3D-related content, such as textures, scripts, etc.) exists—either for individual models or large collections.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Several online marketplaces for 3D content allow individual artists to sell content that they have created, including TurboSquid, MyMiniFactory,Patreon,Sketchfab, CGTrader, and Cults.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Often, the artists' goal is to get additional value out of assets they have previously created for projects.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] By doing so, artists can earn more money out of their old content, and companies can save money by buying pre-made models instead of paying an employee to create one from scratch.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] These marketplaces typically split the sale between themselves and the artist that created the asset, artists get 40% to 95% of the sales according to the marketplace.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] In most cases, the artist retains ownership of the 3D model while the customer only buys the right to use and present the model.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Some artists sell their products directly in their own stores, offering their products at a lower price by not using intermediaries.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The architecture, engineering and construction (AEC) industry is the biggest market for 3D modeling, with an estimated value of $12.13 billion by 2028.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] This is due to the increasing adoption of 3D modeling in the AEC industry, which helps to improve design accuracy, reduce errors and omissions and facilitate collaboration among project stakeholders.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Over the last several years numerous marketplaces specializing in 3D rendering and printing models have emerged.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Some of the 3D printing marketplaces are a combination of models sharing sites, with or without a built in e-com capability.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Some of those platforms also offer 3D printing services on demand, software for model rendering and dynamic viewing of items.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The term 3D printing or three-dimensional printing is a form of additive manufacturing technology where a three-dimensional object is created from successive layers of material.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Objects can be created without the need for complex and expensive molds or assembly of multiple parts.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] 3D printing allows ideas to be prototyped and tested without having to go through a more time-consuming production process.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] 3D models can be purchased from online markets and printed by individuals or companies using commercially available 3D printers, enabling the home-production of objects such as spare parts and even medical equipment.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Open-source tools (for instance Blender, FreeCAD, MeshLab, OpenSCAD) coexist with commercial packages (some examples are: Autodesk Maya/3ds Max/Fusion 360, SolidWorks, CATIA, Cinema 4D, ZBrush, Rhino, Houdini, SketchUp, CLO 3D/Marvelous Designer, Revit, Archicad).
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] The RDF representation of 3D models can be used in reasoning, which enables intelligent 3D applications which, for example, can automatically compare two 3D models by volume.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Overall, these examples are an illustration of 3D modelling being a tool of general purpose representational layer that creates a bridge between sensing to analysis, design, communication and fabrication.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Despite 3D modelling being widely adopted in various domains, several constraints shape how the technology is utilized.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Access and cost remain an issue in many regions of the world.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Commercial licences, training, and capable hardware can be difficult to find in select regions.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] It can also be out of reach for students and small studios that cannot afford it.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Open-source ecosystems and school programs can aid in making this less of an issue, but availability and support are uneven which in turn creates an equity gap in who can learn and apply 3D modelling.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Workflow complexity is another limitation.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] To practice 3D modelling effectively it requires knowledge of many different things.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] A 3D modelling specialist needs to understand topology, UV mapping, rigging, simulation and rendering for DCC.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] For CAD/CAM modelling parametric constraints, tolerances and manufacturing constraints must be known by the developer.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Information schema and coordination are both required for BIM.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Moving assets between tools can introduce incompatibility issues (meshes vs.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] NURBS/solids/parametric features; unit scaling; normals; material definitions), and format conversions may cause data loss without careful management.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] At scale, energy consumption can be large (this is due to high resolution simulations and rendering and dense 3D scans), which directs teams to try and optimize design complexity and adopting more efficient pipelines.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] In research and heritage work, there is another constraint where ethical and policy questions include provenance, licensing and representation (how “authoritative” a reconstruction should be labelled), especially as these reconstruction are utilized for public communication and educational purposes.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Finally, classroom and outreach deployments must take into account pedagogical support: learners need step by step guidance and clear examples and models to follow.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Without this, the tool’s complexity will be more of a barrier that slows students down instead of enabling them to understand and be creative.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] In 3D modeling, simulations are digital processes that copy how things behave in the real world, in a virtual space.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] Without creating actual prototypes, it lets designers and animators test how objects move, interact, or react to forces.
[src:fbx-format/3d-modeling] By recreating processes such as collisions, fluid movement, fabric draping, or particle motion, simulations help increase design accuracy, enhance visual effects, and save both time and materials.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The company was founded in 1982 by John Walker, who was a co-author of the first versions of AutoCAD.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] AutoCAD is the company's flagship computer-aided design (CAD) software and, along with its 3D design software Revit, is primarily used by architects, engineers, and structural designers to design, draft, and model buildings and other structures.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk software has been used in many fields, and on projects from the One World Trade Center to Tesla electric cars.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk became best known for AutoCAD, but now develops a broad range of software for design, engineering, and entertainment—and a line of software for consumers.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The manufacturing industry uses Autodesk's digital prototyping software—including Autodesk Inventor, Autodesk Fusion, and the Autodesk Product Design Suite—to visualize, simulate, and analyze real-world performance using a digital model in the design process.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The company's Revit line of software for building information modeling is designed to let users explore the planning, construction, and management of a building virtually before it is built.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk's Media and Entertainment division creates software for visual effects, color grading, and editing as well as animation, game development, and design visualization.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] 3ds Max and Maya are both 3D animation software used in film visual effects and game development.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The company was founded by John Walker, Daniel Drake, and 14 other programmers in April 1982, who invested $60,000.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Walker founded the company after acquiring Interact, a computer-aided design program that operated on microcomputers running the 8-bit CP/M operating system and two of the new 16-bit systems, the Victor 9000 and the IBM Personal Computer (PC).
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] This tool made it affordable for smaller design, engineering, and architecture companies to create detailed technical drawings.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The program had been developed by Michael Riddle in 1979.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Riddle had struggled to sell the program, and agreed to sell it to Walker in exchange for royalties.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The program was further developed and renamed AutoCAD.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The cofounders were unsure of which area of technology to pursue, so founded the company first and planned as many as five different software applications to see which would succeed.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] AutoCAD went on sale in December 1982 and earned $1.4 million in revenue in its first year.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Walker said in December 1984 that Autodesk was profitable from its first month and had not needed loans or outside investors.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] By then the company had about 10,000 AutoCAD systems installed; it was so successful that for a while Autodesk implied that AutoCAD was the company's name.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The company continued to see itself as a general-purpose software company until new CEO Carol Bartz ended diversification outside computer-aided design in the early 1990s.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk became a public company in 1985.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] John Walker did not enjoy the process of writing the prospectus, relating the process to "lying on the beach or juggling chainsaws".
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Release 2.1 of AutoCAD, released in 1986, included AutoLISP, a built-in Lisp programming language interpreter initially based on XLISP.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] This opened the door for third party developers to extend AutoCAD's functionality, to address a wide range of vertical markets, strengthening AutoCAD's market penetration.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Subsequent to AutoCAD Release 13, the company stopped supporting the Unix environment and the Apple Macintosh platform.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] After AutoCAD Release 14 (R13 was last DOS & Unix release), first shipped in 1997, Autodesk discontinued development under DOS, and focused exclusively on Microsoft Windows.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] AutoCAD has grown to become the most widely used CAD program for 2D non-specialized applications.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The native file formats written by AutoCAD, DXF and DWG, are also widely used for CAD data interoperability.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In 1989, Autodesk's sales grew to over $100,000,000 after just four operational years.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Walker remained a programmer at Autodesk until 1994, when he left due to disagreements with changes at the company.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] With the purchase of Softdesk in 1997, Autodesk started to develop specialty versions of AutoCAD, targeted to broad industry segments, including architecture, civil engineering, and manufacturing.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In 2007, Timothy Vernor sued Autodesk (*Vernor v.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk, Inc.*), alleging that he was entitled to resell "used" copies of AutoCAD software on eBay.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] He had obtained the software from an Autodesk licensee at an office liquidation sale.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] A federal district judge in Washington denied Autodesk's initial motion to dismiss in early 2008.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In February and March 2009, both sides filed motions for summary judgment addressing the issue whether the First Sale Doctrine applies to previously licensed software.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] As such, Autodesk could not pursue an action for copyright infringement against Vernor, who sought to resell used versions of its software on eBay.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk appealed the decision to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit, which reversed the lower court ruling, denying Vernor the right to resale Autodesk software due to Autodesk's nontransferable licensing restrictions.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Supreme Court let stand the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruling.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk introduced a new logo at the TED conference in Long Beach, California, on February 26, 2013.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk announced the largest lay off in its history on November 27, 2017, with the lay off of 1,150 jobs.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] This was in addition to the almost 1,000 job cuts announced in January 2016.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The number of Autodesk employees decreased from approximately 9,200 to 7,200 in less than 2 years.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk updated to its current logo in September 2021.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In 2022, Autodesk moved its headquarters to San Francisco from San Rafael, California—which served as its headquarters since 1994.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In 2025, Autodesk layoffs of 1,350 employees roughly 9% of its workforce as part of restructuring effort to focus on AI and cloud computing.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In January 2026, Autodesk shed about 7% of its global workforce.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] This amounted to approximately 1000 jobs.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In February 2026, Autodesk announced its investment of $200 million in World Labs, an AI spatial intelligence company who specializes in multimodal world models.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The world models developed by World Labs are able to generate realistic 3D worlds that can manipulated, simulated, reconstructed, and interacted with by both human users and AI agents.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk's collaboration with World Labs aims to advance physical-world AI via technical exploration inspired by customer desires and real-world outcomes.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Additionally, World Labs announced their mission to revolutionize storytelling, creativity, robotics, scientific discovery, and more using the new funding and knowledge Autodesk brings.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk will serve as an advisor to World Labs with collaboration in research and world model development.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] According to AutoDesk News, the investment in World Labs is a deliberate choice to pursue a more human centered path when developing and using AI solutions.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The Platform Solutions and Emerging Business (PSEB) division develops and manages the product foundation for most Autodesk offerings across multiple markets, including Autodesk's flagship product AutoCAD, AutoCAD LT, AutoCAD for Mac, and the AutoCAD mobile app (formerly AutoCAD 360).
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk Suites, Subscription and Web Services, which include Autodesk Cloud, Autodesk Labs, and Global Engineering are also part of PSEB.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In what was seen as an unusual step for a maker of high-end business software, Autodesk began offering AutoCAD LT 2012 for Mac through the App Store.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Also part of PSEB is the Autodesk Consumer Product Group, which was created in November 2010 to generate interest in 3-D design and “foster a new wave of designers who hunger for sophisticated software”.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Users range from children, students and artists to makers and DIYers.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk offers certificates in two categories: Autodesk Certified User and Advanced Certified Professional.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The Architecture, Engineering and Construction (AEC) industry group is headquartered in Boston, Massachusetts, in a LEED Platinum building designed and built using Autodesk software.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk's architecture, engineering, and construction solutions include AutoCAD, and Revit, which is its flagship product for relational Building information modeling.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The Autodesk Services Marketplace offering helps its clients train their team in AEC Industry.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Projects that have used software from the Autodesk AEC division include the NASA Ames building, the San Francisco Bay Bridge, the Shanghai Tower, and New York's One World Trade Center.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk Life Sciences is an extensible toolkit for genetic engineering.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] It visualises DNA code (Molecule Viewer), and has a tool for writing DNA code (genetic constructor).
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The tool allows work on molecule-level, rather than nucleobase-level (A, C, G, T) constructs.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk's manufacturing industry group is headquartered in Portland, Oregon.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The company's manufacturing software is used in various manufacturing segments, including industrial machinery, electro-mechanical, tool and die, industrial equipment, automotive components, and consumer products.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk Media and Entertainment products are designed for digital media creation, management, and delivery, from film and television visual effects, color grading, and editing to animation, game development, and design visualization.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk's Media and Entertainment Division is based in Montreal, Quebec.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] It was established in 1999 after Autodesk, Inc. acquired Discreet Logic, Inc. and merged its operations with Kinetix.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In January 2006, Autodesk acquired Alias, a developer of 3D graphics technology.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In October 2008, Autodesk acquired the Softimage brand from Avid.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] The principal product offerings from the Media and Entertainment Division are Flame, Flow Production Tracking, and the Media & Entertainment Collection, which include Maya, 3ds Max, Arnold, MotionBuilder, Mudbox, Golaem, and ReCap Pro.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Much of *Avatar'*s visual effects were created with Autodesk media and entertainment software.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk software enabled *Avatar* director James Cameron to aim a camera at actors wearing motion-capture suits in a studio and see them as characters in the fictional world of Pandora in the film.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk software also played a role in the visual effects of *Alice in Wonderland*, *The Curious Case of Benjamin Button*, *Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 1*, *Inception*, *Iron Man 2*, *King Kong*, *Gladiator*, *Titanic*, and other films.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Walt Disney Animation Studios also utilizes Autodesk Maya for character rigging and animation, being used in films such as Frozen II.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk develops and purchased many specific-purpose renderers but many Autodesk products had been bundled with third-party renderers such as NVIDIA Mental Ray or Iray.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk CFD (formerly Autodesk Simulation CFD) includes modeling and thermal modeling tools for architectural and MEP applications.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Common applications for environmental sustainable design include mechanical ventilation, external flow (wind loading), natural ventilation, and occupant comfort.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Other energy applications include analysis for building energy, solar load, advanced energy and heating and cooling.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk introduced C-FACT, an open-source, science-driven approach to setting greenhouse gas reduction targets, which calls for greenhouse gas (GHG) reductions to be made in proportion to a company's gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Unlike other carbon accounting methods, Autodesk's C-FACT measures carbon dioxide emissions that are proportional to a company's global GDP contribution.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] Autodesk will derive its own targets using this approach through 2020.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In 2006, Autodesk sponsored a PBS program named *e² Design*, which focused on green building design around the world, describing the leaders and technologies that drive sustainable design.
[src:fbx-format/autodesk] In November 2021, the company was added to the Dow Jones Sustainability World Index.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] A **container format** (informally, sometimes called a **wrapper**) or **metafile** is a file format that allows multiple data streams to be embedded into a single file, usually along with metadata for identifying and further detailing those streams.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Notable examples of container formats include archive files (such as the ZIP format) and formats used for multimedia playback (such as Matroska, MP4, and AVI).
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Among the earliest cross-platform container formats were Distinguished Encoding Rules and the 1985 Interchange File Format.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Although containers may identify how data or metadata is encoded, they do not actually provide instructions about how to decode that data.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] A program that can open a container must also use an appropriate codec to decode its contents.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] If the program doesn't have the required algorithm, it can't use the contained data.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] In these cases, programs usually emit an error message that complains of a missing codec, which users may be able to acquire.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Container formats can be made to wrap any kind of data.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Though there are some examples of such file formats (e.g.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Microsoft Windows's DLL files), most container formats are specialized for specific data requirements.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] For example, since audio and video streams can be coded and decoded with many different algorithms, a container format may be used to provide the appearance of a single file format to users of multimedia playback software.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] This is the difference in file-size between two files with the same content in a different container.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Support for advanced codec functionality.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Older formats such as AVI do not support new codec features like B-frames, VBR audio or VFR video natively.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] The format may be "hacked" to add support, but this creates compatibility problems.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Support for advanced content, such as chapters, subtitles, meta-tags, user-data.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] In addition to pure container formats, which specify *only* the wrapper but not the coding, a number of file formats specify *both* a storage layer and the coding, as part of modular design and forward compatibility.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Examples include the JPEG File Interchange Format (JFIF), for containing JPEG data, and Portable Network Graphics (PNG) formats.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] The container file is used to identify and interleave different data types.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] In most cases, the file header, most of the metadata and the synchro chunks are specified by the container format.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] For example, container formats exist for optimized, low-quality, internet video streaming which differs from high-quality Blu-ray streaming requirements.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Container format parts have various names: "chunks" as in RIFF and PNG, "atoms" in QuickTime/MP4, "packets" in MPEG-TS (from the communications term), and "segments" in JPEG.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] The main content of a chunk is called the "data" or "payload".
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Most container formats have chunks in sequence, each with a header, while TIFF instead stores offsets.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Modular chunks make it easy to recover other chunks in case of file corruption or dropped frames or bit slip, while offsets result in framing errors in cases of bit slip.
[src:fbx-format/digital-container-format] Other flexible containers can hold many types of audio and video, as well as other media.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] FBX originated as a replacement file format for Canadian company Kaydara's Filmbox, a software for recording data from motion capture devices.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] Prior to 1996, Filmbox 1.0 used a file format called FLM.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] The format only supported motion data, user preferences and a list of devices used in the capturing of the motion data.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] This data was a serialized version of the libraries (binary dump), containing read/write memory data.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] This method of storing data did not work well with different versions of Filmbox.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] There was also demand from early adopters of Filmbox to implement a target character in a scene with the motion capture data, to enable the visualization of the data in a 3D view with display markers.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] In 1996, Kaydara released a new native file format with Filmbox 1.5 called FBX, which used an object-based model, allowing for the storing of motion, along with 2D, 3D, audio, and video data.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] The format saw wider support from other 3D software packages such as Cinema 4D, SoftImage 3D, PowerAnimator, LightWave 3D, 3D Studio MAX and TurboCAD.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] Filmbox was renamed MotionBuilder in 2002 with the release of version 4.0.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] In 2003, Kaydara launched FBX for Apple's QuickTime Viewer.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] Alias announced its intention to acquire Kaydara on August 8, 2004, reaching an agreement in September.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] A Software Development Kit was developed in 2005 to standardize the object model and allow other software developers to provide plug-ins of their own.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] Alias was acquired by Autodesk on January 10, 2006.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] Later in 2006, support for properties was added to FBX.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] The FBX file format is proprietary; however, the format description is exposed in the FBX Extensions SDK which provides header files for the FBX readers and writers.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] There are two FBX SDK bindings for C++ and Python supplied by Autodesk.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] Blender includes a Python import and export script for FBX, written without using the FBX SDK and The OpenEnded Group's Field includes a Java-based library for loading and extracting parts from a FBX file.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] The Godot game engine can import FBX files without using the FBX SDK.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] In Godot 3.2 this was handled by the Assimp library.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] This was rewritten in Godot 3.3, and replaced by a fork of Facebook's FBX2glTF utility in Godot 4.0.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] Support for the open-source ufbx importer was added for the Godot 4.3 release.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] Godot 4.3 allows both ufbx and FBX2glTF to work in tandem by keeping the previously used importer for a given file as the default importer for that file, however new FBX files in the same project will, by default, use ufbx.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] The FBX can be represented on-disk as either binary or ASCII data; its SDK supports reading and writing both.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] While neither of the formats is documented, the ASCII format is a tree structured document with clearly named identifiers.
[src:fbx-format/fbx] For the FBX binary file format, the Blender Foundation published an unofficial specification, as well as a higher level unofficial spec (work in progress) for how actual data is laid out in FBX (independent of ASCII or binary format).
